{[%evp 0,32,11,47,62,62,62,62,60,49,46,33,33,36,66,22,26,9,42,39,39,31,31,29,13,-1,-1,4,13,-33,-35,-25,7,19,24]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 $5 {The idea is very simple. Since Black is rather cramped on the kingside, he takes this early opportunity to grab space on the queenside. At the same time, it is not so easy for White to make use of his better development. Apart from pawn play with a2-a4 and c2-c4 in different versions, White has a variety of other options.} 7. Nbd2 {This way White is trying to bring the knight closer to Black's king as soon as possible.} (7. Nc3 $5 {Blocking one's own c-pawn like this looks strange, but the point is to finish development quickly and start play on the kingside as soon as possible. Another idea is to meet a5-a4 with b2-b3 after queen and rook are connected.} a4 (7... h6 {You will often see the move ...h7-h6 in this pawn structure. Black wants to proceed with ...Ne7 and answer the eventual Nh4 with ...Bh7. The problem is that after} 8. Be3 Ne7 9. Nh4 $1 Bh7 10. f4 $36 {White's kingside expansion is really fast.}) 8. Bd2 {Anticipating Black's eventual Bb4.} ({One of Black's main points can be seen after} 8. Be3 a3 9. b3 Bb4 10. Nb1 f6 $1 $132 {undermining White's space advantage and speeding up the development.}) 8... Bb4 $5 {Anyway!} ({With a bishop on d2, the standard} 8... a3 {runs into} 9. b3 Bb4 10. Nb5 $1 Be7 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. exd6 Ndf6 13. Bb4 $1 Ne4 14. Qc1 $14 {when White is slightly better.}) 9. a3 (9. Nb5 Be7 $11) 9... Bxc3 $5 {Very often in the 4.Nc3 and 4.Nd2 lines, Black is ready to give up the bishop in order to finish development quickly.} (9... Be7 10. Bd3 $5 Bxd3 11. cxd3 Qa5 12. b3 axb3 13. Qxb3 {And White has a certain initiative.}) 10. bxc3 $5 {Surprisingly, this is the most challenging. As compensation for his weaknesses on the queenside, White has a good prospects on the kingside.} (10. Bxc3 Ne7 11. Bb4 ({Black should always reckon with the typical} 11. Nh4 Be4 {Black will part with the light-squared bishop only on his own terms.} 12. f3 Bg6 13. Be1 {In case of necessity, the bishop is now ready to protect the d4-pawn via the f2-square.} (13. f4 Be4 $132) 13... Qb6 $1 ({White's point can be seen in the line} 13... O-O 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Bf2 c5 16. dxc5 Nxe5 17. b4 $1 $14 {when the potential power of hte bishop pair shouldn't be underestimated.}) 14. f4 Be4 15. b4 O-O $132 {Black has enough counterplay in view of his good control of the light squares. A possible follow-up will be the advance ...f7-f6.}) 11... O-O 12. Nh4 Be4 13. f3 Bg6 14. Nxg6 (14. f4 Be4 $132) 14... hxg6 15. f4 (15. Bd6 Re8 {[%cal Ge7c8]}) 15... c5 $1 {Obtaining good counterplay just in time. Otherwise, after an eventual c2-c3, Black is too passive.} 16. dxc5 Rc8 $132 17. c3 Nxc5 18. Bxc5 Rxc5 19. Qxa4 Nf5 20. Bd3 Qc7 $44) 10... b5 11. Bd3 $1 Bg6 $5 ({After} 11... Ne7 12. Nh4 $1 {again poses some problems for Black, although the position stays double-edged.}) 12. Ng5 ({An interesting alternative is} 12. Bg5 Qa5 13. Rb1 $1 {trying to make it difficult for Black to complete the development. Nevertheless, Black can play} Ne7 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. Qd2 Qd8 16. g3 Ke8 17. Nh4 Qe7 18. f4 Kd8 $1 $132 {with typical counterplay in the style of the French Defence.}) 12... Ne7 13. Qf3 Rf8 $1 ({Black can also castle but it's connected with a pawn sac} 13... O-O 14. Bxg6 Nxg6 15. Qh5 h6 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Qxg6 Qe8 18. Qg3 $14 {And Black has definitely some compensation, but objectively only White can play for a win here.}) 14. h4 ({In case of} 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. h4 Qc7 $13 {the position is rather unclear. Black has enough counterplay on the light squares. In the future, he will follow with ...Nb6-c4. Also, the king can potentially go all the way to the b7-square.}) 14... h6 15. Nh3 Nb6 16. h5 Nc4 $1 {An important intermezzo.} 17. Bxc4 (17. Bc1 Bxd3 18. cxd3 Na5 $132) 17... Be4 18. Qe2 bxc4 19. Rfc1 Qc7 20. Rab1 Kd7 $132 {The position is complex, with mutual chances.}) (7. Ne1 {One of the most typical ideas in this pawn structure. White is planning to expand on the kingside by means of g2-g4 and f2-f4.} a4 {A key move. For the time being, Black has nothing better than winning space on the queenside.} 8. g4 {The most direct approach.} ({Another plan is} 8. Nd3 Ne7 9. c3 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c2] First of all, White wants to mobilize his forces. Only then he will start active actions on the kingside.} h6 {[%cal Gf5h7,Ge7f5] A typical move allowing Black to develop the kingside. The idea is to proceed with ...Bh7 followed by ...Nf5.} 10. Na3 Bh7 11. Nc2 ({Another idea is} 11. Nf4 {planning to answer} Nf5 {with} 12. Bd3 {In this case, however, Black can complete the kingside development by means of} Bxa3 13. bxa3 O-O {with decent counterplay. For instance, after} 14. Rb1 b5 15. Qc2 c5 $1 $132 {all the three results are possible.}) 11... Nf5 12. Nf4 c5 $132 {with sufficient counterplay.}) ({Another typical move is} 8. Bd3 {Generally, Black is happy to exchange minor pieces in view of his insufficient space. Nevertheless, White often goes for the exchange of the light-squared bishops. The reason is that the f5-bishop controls a lot of important squares. A possible follow-up would be} Ne7 9. c3 c5 10. Na3 Bxd3 11. Nxd3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nf5 13. Nc2 Be7 14. Nf4 O-O 15. Ne3 Nh6 $5 $132 {A very nice idea. Black wouldn't like to help his opponent with the development of the bishop. Additionally, Black has very strong counterplay on the queenside.}) 8... Bg6 9. f4 Ne7 10. Nc3 f5 $1 {This is a recurrent idea that Black uses when White starts expanding on the kingside. The most critical continuation is} 11. Nf3 fxg4 12. Ng5 h5 $1 13. Nxe6 Qb6 14. Be3 Bf5 15. Ng5 g6 $132 {with sufficient counterplay.}) ({The continuation} 7. Re1 a4 8. a3 h6 9. Nbd2 {will be covered in the next chapter.}) ({Playing} 7. Be3 {is often premature since the bishop can be vulnerable on e3. Black will immediately try to transfer the knight to f5.} a4 8. c3 ({After} 8. a3 {Black continues in the same fashion -} Bg6 $1 {[%cal Gg8h6,Gh6f5] planning ...Nh6-f5.} 9. c4 {The idea of this move is to gain space on the queenside and put pressure on the centre. The next move is Nc3.} ({It's important to answer} 9. Nbd2 {with} Nh6 $1 {The is the better route towards the f5-square. In case of ...Ne7, White can plan Nh4.} 10. Bxh6 gxh6 11. c4 Qb6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. b3 Be7 $132 {Black's powerful bishops provide enough compensation for the slightly compromised kingside structure.}) 9... Ne7 10. Nc3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Nb6 12. Bd3 Nf5 $1 $132 {Black managed to obtain a very comfortable position. He is going to complete the kingside development without any problems.}) ({If White does not pay attention to our queenside play, we can secure the b4-square for the bishop. For instance, after} 8. Nbd2 a3 9. b3 Bb4 $132 {Black can already fight for the initiative.}) 8... Bg6 $1 {When White's bishop is on e3, it's very typical to quickly transfer the knight to f5 without wasting time on h7-h6.} 9. Nbd2 Nh6 $1 {Another typical way to develop. In order to keep the d8-h4 diagonal open, Black is willing to play with a damaged kingside structure. I have to mention that it's not always fully acceptable for Black, but the bishop on g6 does a good job protecting the weaknesses and being protected by them.} (9... Ne7 $6 10. Nh4 Nf5 11. Nxf5 Bxf5 12. g4 Bg6 13. f4 $40) 10. Bxh6 gxh6 11. Ne1 Be7 12. Ndf3 Qb6 $132) (7. c3 {has no independent meaning - White has to choose some of the typical plans after} a4) 7... a4 8. c3 (8. a3 h6 9. Re1 (9. c4 {- next chapter}) 9... Ne7 10. Nf1 Bg6 {Preparing c7-c5.} 11. Ng3 c5 $1 12. Bb5 (12. c4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nc6 14. Bb5 (14. d5 $6 Nb6 $1) 14... Qa5 $132) 12... c4 $5 13. b3 cxb3 14. cxb3 axb3 15. Qxb3 Nc6 16. Bd2 Be7 $132) (8. Re1 a3 9. c4 {will be subject of the next chapter.}) 8... h6 $1 {The most typical prophylaxis. Black is opening a retreat for the bishop.} (8... a3 $2 9. b4) (8... Ne7 $6 9. Nh4 $16) 9. Re1 (9. Ne1 $5 {Another typical manouevre: White is aiming to put the other knight to f3, aiming to transfer this one to d3 and often f4 next.} c5 $1 {Exploiting the fact that White's regrouping is time-consuming, Black is looking for immediate counterplay.} 10. Bd3 Ne7 11. Ndf3 Qb6 12. Rb1 Bxd3 13. Nxd3 Nc6 14. Be3 cxd4 15. cxd4 Nb4 $1 16. Nxb4 Bxb4 17. Ne1 Bxe1 18. Rxe1 O-O $132) 9... Ne7 10. Nf1 Bg6 $1 {Another typical prophylaxys: Before Black pushes c7-c5, he anticipates the idea dxc5 and Nd4. It is important to mention that it's not always clear where to retreat: g6 or h7. In this particular case makes sense to defend against the unpleasant manouevre Ng3-Nh5.} (10... c5 $2 11. Bb5 a3 12. dxc5 axb2 13. Bxb2 $16) 11. Ng3 c5 12. Bd3 (12. Bb5 {Since dxc5 and Nd4 is not so dangerous now, Black can afford going for the active} a3 $1 13. b3 (13. dxc5 axb2 14. Bxb2 Nc6 15. Nd4 $6 Bxc5 $17) 13... Nc6 $132) 12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc6 14. h4 (14. Nh5 c4 $5 15. Qc2 b5 16. a3 g6 17. Nf4 Qe7 $132) 14... cxd4 $5 (14... c4 {is not so clear now, since White can put pressure on Black's kingside with the queen transfer} 15. Qd2 $1 b5 16. a3 Qe7 17. Qf4 O-O-O 18. Qg4 $14) 15. cxd4 Nb6 16. Nh5 Nc4 $132 {In this French type position, Black has decent counterplay.} *

