{[%evp 0,48,27,14,53,53,53,53,53,40,39,45,33,36,48,37,47,21,23,17,33,34,40,34,34,33,29,33,33,28,28,25,16,0,42,42,47,46,59,16,16,1,1,29,9,39,9,23,72,0,0]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 ({It is instructive to compare the difference caused by the inclusion 6...a5 7.a4.} 6... f6 7. c4 $1 {, and now not the only benefit, but the most illustrative one, can be seen after} fxe5 8. dxe5 Bc5 9. cxd5 exd5 (9... cxd5 10. Nc3 a6 11. Ng5 Qe7 (11... Nxe5 12. Re1 Nf6 13. Bh5+ Nxh5 14. Rxe5 Nf6 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Rxe6+ Kf7 17. Re5 Re8 18. Rxe8 Qxe8 19. Bg5 $1 $16) 12. Bh5+ $1 g6 13. Be2 h5 14. Nf3 Qg7 15. Bg5 Be7 16. Qb3 $16 {1-0 Barria,V (2433) -Garcia Moretti,G (2205) ARG-ch29 email ICCF email 2016}) 10. Nc3 Ne7 11. Na4 $1 {This move is not possible after the a-pawns have moved.} O-O 12. Nxc5 Nxc5 13. Nd4 $16) 7. a4 f6 $1 {Now White has a wide range of choices. Let's start with the dark-squared bishop's development.} 8. Bf4 (8. Be3 fxe5 9. Nxe5 $5 {This seems like the most challenging.} ({Kryvoruchko's move} 9. dxe5 {allows Black to contest the important a7-g1 diagonal. Still, the position remains very complex.} Bc5 10. Nd4 $5 (10. Bxc5 Nxc5 11. Nd4 Ne7 (11... Nh6 $5 $132) 12. Bh5+ (12. Qd2 $5 {was the best chance for White in our game} O-O 13. Qe3 Na6 14. Na3 (14. g4 c5 $132) 14... Nc7 15. c3 Be4 16. Qd2 $1 Nf5 17. Nxf5 Bxf5 18. Nc2 {With some initiative for White in a complex position.}) 12... g6 13. Be2 Qb6 (13... Qc7 $5) 14. g4 $2 (14. Ra3 $5 h5 $1 15. Qc1 Bg4 16. Nd2 Nf5 $13) 14... Be4 $1 {With this move I took over the initiative and won a nice game:} 15. Nc3 h5 16. f3 O-O-O 17. fxe4 dxe4 18. Qd2 hxg4 19. Bxg4 Nf5 20. Bxf5 gxf5 21. Nce2 Nd7 22. Ra3 Nxe5 23. Rb3 Qc5 24. Qc3 Nc4 25. Kh1 e3 26. Nf3 e5 27. Nxe5 Qd5+ 28. Nf3 Nd2 29. Qg7 c5 30. Rd3 Nxf3 31. Qg2 Rxh2+ 32. Qxh2 Nd4+ 33. Kg1 Nxe2+ 34. Qxe2 Rg8+ 35. Kh2 Qe5+ 36. Kh1 Qe4+ {0-1 Kryvoruchko,Y (2658)-Eljanov,P (2697) Bundesliga 2223 Germany 2022 (1.1)}) 10... Bxd4 $1 {Again, it's very typical for the Advanced Caro-Kann that Black gives up this bishop to keep the one on f5, which is usually the more important piece.} 11. Bxd4 Ne7 12. f4 O-O 13. Nd2 (13. h4 h6 14. h5 b6 15. g4 Bh7 16. Qd2 Qc7 17. Nc3 Rf7 $13) 13... b6 14. Be3 Nc5 15. Nf3 h6 16. Nd4 Be4 $132) 9... Bd6 $1 (9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 {Black is too passive here.} Bg6 {0-1 Cardoso Cardoso,J (2486) -Henriquez Villagra,C (2587) Jamundi Fortalece Sede op 2022 (4)} (10... Ne7 11. f4 Bg6 12. Nd2 Nf5 13. Bf2 Be7 14. Nb3 O-O 15. c3 b6 16. g4 Nh6 17. Nd4 $14) 11. Bg4 $1 Bf7 12. c4 $36) 10. f4 (10. g4 Bg6 11. f4 Qb6 $5 $132) 10... Ne7 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nd2 O-O {This type of structure is double-edged and can be strategically dangerous for Black. But here Black has enough dynamic resources.} 13. h4 (13. c3 Nf6 14. Ndf3 Qe8 15. Ng5 Ne4 $1 $132) 13... h5 $1 14. gxh5 Nf5 15. Bf2 Be8 16. Ndf3 Bxe5 17. dxe5 Bxh5 18. Ng5 Bxe2 19. Qxe2 Qe8 $1 $132) 8... Ne7 $1 {Threatening Ng6 and forcing White to release the tension.} (8... g5 {is often the way to achieve counterplay in positions of this type, but here it's clearly premature:} 9. Bg3 h5 10. exf6 Qxf6 11. Ne5 $1 {Giving Black no time to play h5-h4.} Qh6 12. Nxd7 Kxd7 13. Be5 $36) (8... Qb6 $6 9. Bd3 $1 (9. b3 $6 Ne7 $132 {0-1 Ayush,S (2267) -Sethuraman,S (2645) Asian Continental op 19th Delhi 2022 (8)}) 9... Ne7 10. exf6 gxf6 11. c4 $16) 9. exf6 Nxf6 (9... gxf6 $2 10. Nh4 $1 Bg6 11. Bg4 f5 12. Be2 Bf7 13. Nd2 (13. Bd6 $2 Bg7 $13 {1/2-1/2 Zhigalko,S (2612)-Daneshvar,B (2419) Wch Rapid Almaty 2022 (2)}) 13... Nc8 14. Nhf3 $16) 10. Bd3 $1 {The only way to create problems for Black. Otherwise, Black will follow with the natural ...Ng6 followed by either ...Bd6 or ...Be7.} ({Harmless is} 10. Bg5 Ng6 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Qd7 13. Re1 Bd6 14. Qe2 Kf7 $132 {Black has sufficient counterplay since he managed to cover all the weaknesses. The next moves will be ...Rae8 followed by ...Rhf8, and ...Kg8. White should always watch out for the potential ...e6-e5.}) ({Nothing gives} 10. c4 Ng6 11. Bg3 Nh5 12. Nc3 Be7 13. Bd3 O-O $132 {Once again, Black has more than sufficient counterplay.}) ({In case of} 10. Ne5 Ng6 11. Nxg6 {Both recaptures give Black good counterplay.} ({The structure arising after} 11. Be3 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Bg4 Qc7 14. Bxf5 exf5 {is acceptable for Black. If he manages to consolidate, he can be even better due to his good central control and active minor pieces.} 15. Re1 Nc5 16. Qf3 g6 17. Nd2 O-O-O 18. Rad1 Kb8 $13 {Even though the position remains unclear, Black has nothing to worry about. After ...Ne6 followed by ...Be7, Black can even consider expanding on the kingside.}) 11... Bxg6 {The most natural recapture.} ({A very interesting option would have been} 11... hxg6 $5 {It turns out that Black can use the h-file for the purposes of his attack.} 12. Nd2 Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Nf3 Ng4 $1 15. h3 ({The cold-blooded} 15. g3 Be4 16. Ra3 {would lead to equality after} Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Nxh2 18. Re1 O-O-O $11 {The position is objectively equal but playable for both sides.}) 15... Be4 $1 16. Re1 $1 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Qh2+ 18. Kf1 Nh6 $1 19. Rxe6+ Kf7 20. Re5 Rhf8 $1 $44 {Black has more than sufficient compensation for the pawn in view of White's vulnerable king.}) 12. Nd2 Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Nf3 Nd7 15. Ra3 O-O 16. c4 Rae8 $132 {Black managed to cover his weaknesses abd mobilize all his pieces. In some cases, White's position may turn out to be slightly overextended.}) 10... Ng6 $1 {Black must finish development quickly. Taking back with the pawn on f5 is desirable, as e6 is Black's main weakness.} 11. Bxf5 exf5 (11... Nxf4 $2 12. Re1 $16) 12. Bg5 (12. Be5 Nxe5 13. Qe2 Qc7 14. dxe5 Ne4 15. c4 O-O-O $132) 12... Qd7 $1 {A non-standard way to get dynamic counterplay. White now has two conceptually different approaches:} 13. Bxf6 {The positional approach. White creates weaknesses and hopes to exploit them later.} ({With} 13. c4 $5 {, White can continue playing dynamically:} dxc4 {The most precise continuation. The following lines show that Black has decent counterplay in all the lines.} (13... Ne4 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Nc3 Bb4 16. h4 $1 h6 17. Bc1 O-O 18. h5 Ne7 19. Ne5 Qd8 20. Bf4 $36) 14. Qe2+ Be7 15. Qxc4 (15. Nbd2 b5 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd5 18. e6 Qc7 $13) (15. Na3 b5 16. Ne5 Qd5 17. Rfd1 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Qe4 $1 19. Re1 Qxe2 20. Rxe2 Nd5 21. Bxe7 Kxe7 22. axb5 cxb5 23. Nxb5 g6 24. Nd6 c3 25. bxc3 Nxc3 26. Rc2 Ne4 $11) 15... Ne4 $1 {Keeping control of the e5-square while blocking the e-file as long as necessary.} 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nc3 O-O-O 18. g3 Rhe8 19. Qb3 h5 $132) 13... gxf6 14. Nbd2 Bd6 15. c3 (15. Re1+ Kf7 16. Kh1 Rhg8 17. c3 Kg7 18. Nf1 Kh8 19. Qc2 Rg7 20. Ne3 Ne7 21. Nh4 Rg5 $132 {Just like in the mainline, Black can generate sufficient counterplay on the g-file.}) 15... O-O 16. Ne1 (16. Qc2 Kh8 17. Kh1 Rg8 $132) 16... Kh8 {At first the engine shows an edge for White, but then doesn't seem able to prove it.} 17. Nd3 Rg8 18. Qh5 (18. Kh1 f4 $1 19. Qh5 (19. Nf3 Nf8 $1 20. Nh4 Rg4 $132) 19... Ne7 20. Rae1 Nf5 $132 {transposes to the mainline.}) 18... f4 $5 {Gaining more space on the kingside and preparing a knight transfer to f5.} (18... Nf4 $5 $132) 19. Kh1 Ne7 $1 20. Rae1 Nf5 21. Rg1 Rg6 22. Qf3 Nh4 23. Qh5 Qf5 24. Qxh4 Qxd3 $11 *

