{[%evp 0,32,39,46,71,76,56,61,61,52,45,32,35,44,68,34,38,4,33,26,7,33,-1,-3,19,-13,30,-12,32,26,26,26,68,-29,58]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 7. a4 f6 8. Nbd2 {dangerous plan because White is planning to transfer the knight to the best square- b3 where he is controlling very important d4 and c5 squares} (8. Bd3 {A logical and sound choice. White is trying to exploit the weakened light squares.} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 (9. cxd3 Nh6 $1 {This looks somewhat unconventional, combined with f7-f6, but is clearly the best move here. The knight is heading to f7.} 10. Bxh6 (10. Qe2 {Immediately putting pressure on e6 looks logical but is not very dangerous for Black.} Nf7 11. exf6 Qxf6 12. Re1 Nd8 $1 13. Bg5 (13. Na3 h6 $132) 13... Qg6 (13... Qf5 $5) 14. Bxd8 Kxd8 15. Qxe6 Qxe6 16. Rxe6 Ra6 $5 (16... Bb4 $5 $44) 17. Ng5 Nf6 $44 18. Nf7+ Kd7 19. Rxf6 gxf6 20. Nxh8 Rb6 21. Nd2 Bg7 $15) 10... gxh6 {With both pawn structures being compromised, the game tends to be dynamically balanced.} 11. g3 (11. Na3 f5 $5 12. Nc2 Nb8 $1 $132 {Rerouting the knight towards b4 while opening an escape for the king towards the queenside.}) 11... Bg7 (11... f5 $5 12. Nh4 Nb8 $132) 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. Qe2 Ra6 14. Ra3 Rb6 15. Rb3 Rxb3 16. Nxb3 Qb6 $132) 9... fxe5 10. dxe5 Qc7 11. Qe2 (11. Re1 Nc5 12. Qe2 Ne7 13. Nd4 Nf5 $1 14. Nxf5 exf5 15. Nd2 Ne6 16. Nb3 Be7 $132) 11... Ne7 12. Nbd2 (12. c4 O-O-O 13. Nc3 Nc5 $132) (12. Ng5 Qxe5 $11) 12... Ng6 13. Nb3 {The position is double-edged, but Black needs to play very precisely:} (13. Ng5 Qxe5 $11) 13... c5 $1 14. Ng5 Qb6 $1 {Not only protecting e6 but also anticipating ideas of Qg4 and f2-f4.} (14... Qxe5 15. Qxe5 Ngxe5 16. Nxe6 $16) (14... Qc6 15. Qg4 $1 Ra6 16. f4 $16) 15. f4 (15. Qg4 Ra6 $15 16. f4 $4 c4+ $19) 15... Be7 $1 16. Nf3 O-O $5 (16... c4+ $5 {is the more straightforward but also double-edged continuation.} 17. Nbd4 O-O 18. g3 Ndxe5 $1 19. fxe5 Rxf3 20. Qxf3 Qxd4+ 21. Be3 Qxe5 22. Rae1 Bf6 {With an unclear position.}) 17. g3 Nh8 $5 18. Be3 Nf7 19. Nbd2 Nb8 $5 $132 {The position remains highly complex.}) (8. Nh4 {Trying to punish Black's strategy in the most straightforward way.} fxe5 9. Nxf5 exf5 10. c4 $5 (10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Re1 {This looks dangerous, but actually Black has more than one way to reach a satisfactory position.} (11. Bh5+ Ng6 12. Re1+ Be7 13. Bg5 Qc7 $5 $132) 11... Kf7 (11... Bd6 $5 12. c4 Nf6 13. cxd5 O-O 14. dxc6 bxc6 15. Bf4 Kh8 $132) 12. Bh5+ Ng6 13. Qf3 Nf6 14. Qxf5 Bb4 15. Qe6+ Kf8 16. c3 Bc5 17. Bg5 Qe8 $11) 10... dxc4 11. Nd2 (11. Bxc4 Ngf6 12. Na3 (12. Qb3 Bb4 {The bishop is an invaluable defender here, preventing Re1 for the moment and blocking the b-file.} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Be6 Nfd7 $5 {Black's position may look very fragile, but in fact White is lacking development and coordination, and he must play precisely to avoid a strategically worse position.} 15. Bxf5 Rf8 16. Na3 Qf6 $132) 12... Bd6 13. d5 cxd5 14. Bxd5 Bxa3 15. Rxa3 Nc5 $11 {The bishops are potentially dangerous, but Black is a pawn up and certainly not worse.}) 11... Bb4 12. Nxc4 e4 13. Bd2 Ndf6 $1 14. Bxb4 axb4 15. Qb3 Nd5 16. Qg3 Kf8 17. Qe5 Nh6 $132 {White needs to prove his compensation before Black fully consolidates, which does not look like an easy task.}) (8. c3 {doesn't look very critical or dangerous, but is a useful move that should not be dismissed.} fxe5 9. dxe5 Bc5 10. Nd4 (10. Nbd2 Ne7 11. Nb3 Ba7 12. Nbd4 O-O 13. Nh4 Nc5 $13) 10... Nxe5 (10... Ne7 $5 11. g4 Bxd4 12. cxd4 Bxb1 13. Rxb1 O-O $13 {0-1 Pranesh,M (2404)-Ashraf,A (2289) Abu Dhabi Masters 28th 2022 (5)}) 11. g4 Bxb1 12. Nxe6 Qe7 13. Nxc5 Qxc5 14. Rxb1 Nf6 $132) (8. Re1 fxe5 9. dxe5 Bc5 10. Nbd2 Ne7 11. Nb3 Bb6 12. Nbd4 O-O 13. c3 {1-0 Cheparinov,I (2623)-Ghasi,A (2587) Wch Blitz Almaty 2022 (13)} h6 14. h3 Qe8 $5 (14... Ng6 $5 $13) 15. Nh4 Be4 $13) (8. exf6 Ngxf6 9. Nh4 Bd6 10. Nxf5 exf5 11. c4 O-O 12. Nd2 Kh8 $132) 8... Nh6 $1 {White has blocked the bishop for one moment, so Black should immediately seize the opportunity.} 9. Nb3 Nf7 10. Re1 (10. Nh4 fxe5 11. Nxf5 exf5 12. dxe5 Nfxe5 13. Re1 Kf7 $1 14. f4 Nc4 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16. Qe2 Nf6 17. Qe6+ Kg6 {looks funny, but Black's king is actually safer than his rival.} 18. Qxc4 Bd6 19. Be3 Re8 $132) 10... g5 $5 {A typical way to get counterplay, that works well here. At the same time, Black prevents the threat Nh4.} 11. Bd2 {Putting pressure on a5 and anticipating Bb4-ideas, which can lead to very messy and unclear positions:} (11. c4 Bb4 $1 (11... g4 12. Nh4 Be4 13. Bxg4 fxe5 14. Nf3 $15) 12. Bd2 (12. cxd5 Bxe1 13. Qxe1 exd5 $15) 12... Bxd2 13. Qxd2 (13. Nbxd2 O-O 14. exf6 Qxf6 $132) 13... g4 $1 {And now some insane lines:} 14. Nh4 Be4 $1 15. Bxg4 $1 fxe5 16. Bxe6 (16. f3 Qxh4 17. Bxe6 Bxf3 18. Bxf7+ Kxf7 19. gxf3 Qf6 $15) 16... Qxh4 17. cxd5 Rg8 18. Bxd7+ (18. g3 Ng5) 18... Kd8 $1 (18... Kxd7 $2 19. Nc5+) 19. g3 Ng5 $1 20. Re3 Qh5 $132) 11... Bg7 (11... h5 $6 12. exf6 Qxf6 {1-0 Nitish,B (2416)-Ashraf,A (2289) Dubai op 22nd 2022 (5)} 13. c4 $1 g4 14. cxd5 $1 gxf3 15. dxc6 fxe2 16. cxd7+ Kxd7 17. Qxe2 $40) 12. Bd3 $5 (12. c4 O-O 13. cxd5 exd5 $1 {Black should not be afraid of ghosts. He can defend against all of White's threats here.} 14. e6 (14. exf6 Qxf6 15. h3 g4 (15... h5 $6 16. Nh2) 16. hxg4 Bxg4 $132) 14... Bxe6 15. Bd3 Re8 16. Qc2 h6 $1 17. Bh7+ Kh8 18. Bg6 Kg8 {White can try to play on, but the position remains balanced.} 19. Nc5 Nxc5 20. dxc5 d4 21. Rad1 Bg4 22. Qb3 Qd7 $13) (12. exf6 Qxf6 13. Ne5 (13. h3 h5 {Here White has to play very precisely to hold the balance:} 14. c4 $1 g4 15. cxd5 $1 gxf3 16. dxc6 (16. dxe6 Bxe6 17. Bc4 Nde5 $1 $15) 16... fxe2 17. cxd7+ Kf8 18. Qxe2 Rd8 19. Nc5 (19. Bxa5 Rxd7 20. Nc5 Rd5 $132) 19... b6 20. Nxe6+ Bxe6 21. Qxe6 Qxe6 22. Rxe6 Rxd7 23. Rxb6 Bxd4 $11) 13... Ndxe5 14. dxe5 Qh6 $1 15. Bh5 (15. Bd3 O-O 16. Bxf5 exf5 17. e6 Nd6 18. Bxa5 Rfe8 $11) 15... O-O 16. h4 Bg6 $1 17. Bxg6 Qxg6 18. h5 Qh6 19. Bxa5 Bxe5 $132) 12... Bxd3 13. cxd3 O-O 14. exf6 Qxf6 15. h3 h5 16. Re3 Rae8 $132 {For the a5-pawn, Black will obtain a strong initiative on the kingside.} *

