{[%evp 0,24,46,45,71,56,61,61,61,19,24,29,21,24,23,23,17,8,-17,-34,-38,-22,4,-32,-44,-65,-74]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 e6 5. Nb3 {Preventing c6-c5 is clearly White's main choice in this position, but on rare occasions, a few other moves have been tried:} (5. g4 Bg6 6. Ne2 c5 $1 {This is similar to 4.Nc3 e6 5.g4. In both cases, Black is OK.} 7. h4 h5 8. Nf4 Ne7 $1 (8... Bh7 9. Nxh5 cxd4 10. Nb3 Nc6 11. Nxd4 Nge7 12. c3 Nxe5 13. Bg5 $132 {1-0 Vallejo Pons,F (2693) -Karpov,A (2644) Donostia-A San Sebastian 2009 (7)}) 9. Nxg6 Nxg6 10. gxh5 Nxh4 11. Qg4 Nf5 12. dxc5 Qc7 13. Nf3 Nc6 14. Bg5 Bxc5 15. O-O-O Bxf2 $1 16. Kb1 Ne3 17. Bxe3 Bxe3 18. Qxg7 O-O-O $132 {1/2-1/2 Relyea,A (1622)-Gross Winter,G (2251) Champion's League 12/C4 email ICCF email 2012 [4]}) (5. Ngf3 {A strange and somewhat inconsistent move. Black has a good position after the logical} c5 $1 6. dxc5 $6 Bxc5 7. Nb3 Bb6 8. Nfd4 Ne7 9. h4 h6 10. h5 Nbc6 11. Nxf5 Nxf5 12. g4 {0-1 Kalogeris,I (2368)-Sumets,A (2524) EU-ch Rapid Katowice 2021 (6)} Nfd4 $1 13. f4 Nxb3 14. axb3 f6 $15) ({After} 5. h4 h5 6. Nb3 c5 $5 $132 {is not the only way to play, but it seems like the inclusion of h2-h4 and h7-h5 is in Black's favour, as he now has good control over the light squares on the kingside.}) 5... Nd7 6. Nf3 (6. c3 {is not flexible, since White loses the option to play c2-c4 in one move.} f6 $5 7. f4 fxe5 8. dxe5 Nh6 (8... c5 $5 $132) 9. Nf3 (9. Nd4 Bc5 10. Ngf3 Bxd4 $1 11. Nxd4 (11. cxd4 Bg4 12. Bd3 Nf5 $132) 11... Nc5 12. Be3 Qh4+ 13. g3 Qe7 14. Nxf5 Nxf5 $132) 9... c5 $1 (9... Be7 10. Be3 (10. Nbd4 $5 O-O 11. Be2) 10... O-O $132 {0-1 Rozhkov,V (2319) -Harutjunyan,G (2430) Voronezh op-A 20th 2016 (7)}) 10. Be3 Be7 11. Be2 O-O $132) 6... Qc7 $5 {This is the line I recommend because it seems like the most flexible approach to prepare c6-c5.} 7. Be3 {Delaying the development of the light-squared bishop, to be able to play Bb5 in some lines. Black should meet this strategy with immediate counterplay in the centre.} (7. c3 {An interesting waiting move with the idea to answer} f6 $1 (7... c5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nxc5 Qxc5 10. Nd4 Ne7 11. Bb5 Qc7 12. O-O O-O 13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. Bg5 f6 15. exf6 gxf6 16. Bh6 $36) {with} 8. Bf4 {But after} fxe5 9. Nxe5 Bd6 10. Qh5+ $1 g6 11. Qe2 h5 $5 12. g3 (12. Qe3 O-O-O $132) 12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Be7 14. h4 (14. Nd4 Nh6 15. Bg2 g5 16. Bd2 O-O-O $132) 14... Nh6 15. Bg2 O-O-O 16. Nd4 c5 $132 {, Black has sufficient counterplay nonetheless.}) (7. Nh4 {A logical approach, but Black has a good answer in} Be4 $1 8. f3 Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. f4 Ne7 11. Be3 Nf5 12. Bf2 O-O-O (12... c5 $5 13. c3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Bb4+ 15. Nd2 Qb6 16. a3 Be7 $132) 13. g4 Nh4 14. Qe2 f6 15. Bg3 g5 $1 $132) (7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 c5 $1 9. c4 Ne7 10. O-O cxd4 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nbxd4 Be7 13. Bg5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxg5 15. Qb5+ Kf8 16. Rfe1 a6 17. Qb3 Re8 $15 {1/2-1/2 Rublevsky,S (2698) -Riazantsev,A (2684) RUS GP rap final Rostov on Don rapid 2014 (3.2)}) (7. Bf4 {Not the most obvious square for the bishop and hardly the best.} Ne7 8. h3 (8. Be2 Ng6 $1 9. Bg3 a5 10. a4 Be7 $15) 8... h6 9. c3 O-O-O $5 $132) (7. a4 {was played by a young star, but another young star responded soundly:} a6 $5 {, and it seems like this inclusion of moves is in Black's favor. After securing the b5-square, Black can even recapture with the knight on c5 (after an eventual c6-c5).} 8. Be2 (8. Be3 $6 f6 (8... c5 $1 $15) 9. Bf4 fxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 (10... Bd6 $5 $132) 11. Bxe5 Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Bd3 Ne7 14. O-O O-O 15. Re1 Rae8 (15... Ng6 $132) 16. a5 (16. g3 $1 Ng6 $6 17. f4 $1 $16) 16... Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Ng6 $11 {0-1 (102) Abdusattorov,N (2688)-Keymer,V (2686) Biel 2022}) 8... c5 9. dxc5 Nxc5 $5 10. Nbd4 Bg4 $132) 7... f6 8. exf6 (8. Bf4 fxe5 9. Nxe5 Bd6 10. Qh5+ g6 11. Qe2 h5 $132) 8... Ngxf6 9. Bd3 Bd6 {The weakness on e6 is not a problem, since Black is very active.} 10. Ng5 Nf8 $5 (10... Qc8 $5 11. O-O O-O $132) 11. Bxf5 $6 (11. Qe2 O-O-O $132) 11... exf5 12. Qe2 O-O-O $17 {0-1 Vanek,P (2215)-Gregor,J (2241) CZE-chT2c 0506 Czech Republic 2005 (1.1)} *

