{[%evp 0,38,27,7,64,53,53,53,53,16,22,16,16,19,26,33,10,13,13,4,7,-12,-9,-5,-6,-27,15,-5,-14,-28,-21,-17,-2,-5,-11,-16,-16,-41,-5,-10,-8]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 e6 5. Nb3 Nd7 6. Nf3 Qc7 7. Be2 c5 (7... f6 {may be playable but looks rather dangerous:} 8. O-O (8. Bf4 $5 fxe5 9. dxe5 c5 10. Nh4 $1 Ne7 11. Nxf5 Nxf5 12. Bg4 Qc6 13. O-O O-O-O 14. Re1 $14) 8... fxe5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nfd4 $1 Nf6 11. f4 (11. Bg5 $6 Ne4 $15 {0-1 Mishra,A (2535) -Tari,A (2654) Chessable Masters Prelim chess24.com INT rapid 2022 (11)}) 11... Neg4 12. h3 {Now Black has to give up the piece for interesting compensation that doesn't seem quite sufficient, though.} h5 13. hxg4 hxg4 14. Bd3 $1) 8. dxc5 (8. O-O c4 9. Nbd2 h6 10. c3 Ne7 {transposes to the next chapter.}) 8... Bxc5 9. Nxc5 (9. Nfd4 Ne7 10. Nxc5 Qxc5 {transposes.}) 9... Qxc5 $5 {Threatening c2 immediately and gaining extra options in some lines due to the queen's active position.} ({Also possible but less precise is} 9... Nxc5 10. Nd4 Ne7 11. O-O a6 12. a4 (12. Re1 $5 Bg6 13. Bf1 $6 O-O (13... Nc6 14. Nxc6 Qxc6 15. Be3 O-O 16. Bd4 b5 17. h4 h6 18. h5 Bh7 19. Re3 $16 {1-0 Goganov,A (2571)-Mikhailovsky,V (2197) Bryansk Zilberstein Memorial 5th rapid 2021 (7)}) 14. h4 h6 15. h5 Bh7 16. a4 $14) 12... O-O 13. Be3 Rac8 14. f4 Be4 {1/2-1/2 Rublevsky,S (2688)-Grachev,B (2693) RUS-chT 20th Loo 2013 (4)} 15. Bf2 $5 Nf5 16. a5 $14) 10. c3 (10. Nd4 Ne7 11. f4 Be4 12. Be3 (12. O-O $2 Bxc2 $17 {One of the points behind Qxc5.}) 12... Qb4+ $1 13. Kf2 (13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Bxd2 (14. Kxd2 g5 $5 15. fxg5 Bxg2 16. Rhg1 Be4 $132) 14... Nf5 $1 {A typical idea to fight for the center.} 15. Nxf5 exf5 $1 {Fortifying this fantastic bishop on e4.} 16. O-O (16. Kf2 f6 17. exf6 Nxf6 18. c3 Kf7 19. h3 (19. Be3 Ng4+ $11) 19... Rae8 20. Rae1 h5 $5 $132) 16... h5 $5 17. c4 dxc4 18. Bxc4 Rh6 19. Be2 h4 20. Rac1 Nb6 21. Bb5+ Bc6 $132) 13... O-O 14. Qe1 Qb6 $1 {After disrupting White's coordination, Black's queen can return.} 15. Rf1 (15. Nf5 Qd8 $15) 15... f6 (15... Rac8 16. b3 f6 17. exf6 Rxf6 18. Kg1 Rg6 19. Rf2 Nf6 20. Rc1 Qd6 21. c4) 16. exf6 Rxf6 17. Kg1 e5 18. fxe5 (18. Nf5 Qe6 $13) 18... Nxe5 19. Qc3 Rxf1+ 20. Rxf1 Qg6 21. Nf3 N7c6 $11) (10. Be3 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qb6 12. Bc3 Ne7 13. Nd4 Bg6 $132) 10... Ne7 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 (12. Bf4 Qb6 $5 {With the interesting idea to provoke Qd2 and only then attack the e5-pawn.} (12... Ng6 $2 13. Be3 Qc7 14. Nd4 $16 {And Black has to deal with the threat g2-g4.}) 13. Qd2 (13. b3 Ng6 14. Be3 Qa5 $1 $132 15. Nd4 Ndxe5 16. b4 (16. g4 $6 Be4 17. f3 $2 Qxc3 $19) 16... Qc7 17. Nxf5 exf5 18. Qxd5 b6 19. Bd4 Rfe8 $132) 13... Ng6 14. Be3 Qc7 15. Nd4 Ndxe5 $1 {This reveals the point of Black's play: The queen no longer supports g2-g4.} 16. Nxf5 exf5 17. Qxd5 Rfd8 18. Qb5 f4 19. Bd4 f3 $36) 12... Qb6 $5 (12... Qc7 $5 {looks lik an equally good alternative.} 13. Bf4 Ng6 14. Bg3 Qb6 $1 {An improvement. Again, the idea is to define the position of White's queen first.} (14... Bg4 15. Nd4 $1 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 a6 17. h4 Ne7 18. h5 $36 {1/2-1/2 Gledura,B (2605)-Lupulescu,C (2631) HUN-chT 1718 Hungary 2017 (1.1)}) 15. Nd4 (15. Qc1 Bg4 16. h3 (16. Nd4 Bxe2 17. Rxe2 Nb8 $1 18. h4 h6 19. h5 Ne7 20. f4 Nbc6 21. Bf2 Nxd4 22. Bxd4 Qa6 23. Qd2 Nc6 $132) 16... Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Ne7 18. Bg4 Nc5 19. Qc2 Rfc8 20. Bf4 a5 21. Be3 Qc7 22. f4 b5 $132) (15. Qd2 Nc5 {[%cal Gc5e4] And the queen is in an awkward spot.}) 15... Qxb2 16. Nxf5 exf5 17. Qxd5 f4 18. Rab1 Qxc3 19. Qxd7 fxg3 20. hxg3 Nxe5 21. Qxb7 g6 $11) (12... Nc6 13. Be3 Qa5 14. Nd4 Bg6 15. f4 $14) 13. a4 (13. Bf1 Nc6 14. Nd4 Bg6 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. h4 h6 (16... h5 $5 17. b3 a5 $132) 17. h5 Bf5 $1 (17... Bh7 18. b3 (18. b4 $1 a5 19. a4 Qc7 20. Qg4 Kh8 21. Qf4 $14 {[%csl Gf7]}) 18... a5 19. Bf4 Kh8 $132 {1/2- (108) 1/2 Gledura,B (2613)-Berkes,F (2658) Budapest Hetenyi Memorial GM 2017 (8)}) 18. b4 a5 19. a4 Qc7 20. Qf3 Rfb8 21. Qg3 Kh8 $132) 13... a6 14. h3 {Preventing Bg4.} (14. Bf1 Nc6 15. Nd4 Ndxe5 16. Nxf5 exf5 17. b4 Rfe8 18. h3 Qd8 $132) (14. a5 Qc7 15. Bf4 Bg4 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Nc6 18. c4 dxc4 19. Qd6 Qxd6 20. exd6 Nc5 $132) 14... Be4 15. a5 Qd8 $1 {It's important to be precise here.} ({After} 15... Qc7 16. Nd4 $1 {, the structure should be favourable for White:} Nc6 (16... Nxe5 $2 17. Bf4 $16) 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Bf4 c5 19. b4 $14) 16. Bg5 (16. Nd4 Nxe5) 16... h6 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Bf1 Nb8 $5 19. Nd4 Nc6 $132 *

