{[%evp 0,42,27,7,69,53,53,53,53,16,16,16,13,29,26,13,47,-14,35,17,29,23,21,-14,12,13,20,10,3,6,25,6,15,5,34,30,32,24,27,11,-11,7,13,8,39]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 e6 5. Nb3 Nd7 6. Nf3 Qc7 7. Be2 c5 8. c3 {Stabilising the central pawn chain looks like the most principled continuation.} h6 $5 {A flexible approach: Black is waiting for White to castle short in view of the rather dangerous manoeuvre Nd2-f1-e3/g3.} ({The immediate} 8... c4 {illustrates the difference:} 9. Nbd2 h6 10. Nf1 $1 Ne7 11. Ne3 (11. Ng3 $5 Bg6 12. Nh4 Bh7 13. f4 O-O-O 14. O-O $36) 11... Bh7 12. g3 b5 13. O-O Nc6 14. Nh4 Be7 15. Nhg2 a5 $6 (15... O-O 16. f4 Rad8 17. f5 Ndxe5 $1 18. dxe5 d4 $132) 16. f4 f5 17. g4 $16 {0-1 Dominguez Perez,L (2754)-Van Foreest,J (2678) Zagreb SuperUnited Blitz 2022 (14)}) {Now White has the choice between two moves that lead to very much different positions.} 9. O-O (9. dxc5 Bxc5 (9... Nxc5 {is dangerous due to} 10. Nfd4 {, followed by Bb5+.} Ne7 $2 {loses immediately after} 11. Nb5 $18) 10. Nxc5 Nxc5 $5 {After a pair of pieces has been exchanged, Black can and should take with the knight.} (10... Qxc5 11. Nd4 Ne7 12. O-O O-O 13. g4 Bh7 14. Be3 Qc7 15. f4 a6 16. Qe1 $14) 11. Be3 (11. Nd4 Ne7 12. Nxf5 $6 (12. Be3) 12... Nxf5 13. g4 Nh4 14. Qd4 h5 15. gxh5 Nf5 16. Qb4 a6 17. Kf1 O-O-O $36 {0-1 Soumya,S (2377)-Esipenko,A (2625) Abu Dhabi op 26th 2019 (4)}) 11... Ne7 12. Nd4 a6 13. a4 (13. O-O O-O 14. f4 b5 15. Qd2 (15. g4 Be4 16. Qd2 Ng6 17. Rad1 f6 18. exf6 Rxf6 19. f5 exf5 20. Nxf5 Raf8 $132) 15... Rac8 $132) 13... O-O 14. O-O Be4 $5 {Provoking f2-f3, which is almost always in Black's favour.} 15. f3 Bh7 16. f4 f6 $1 {This typical undermining move provides Black with sufficient counterplay:} 17. exf6 (17. b4 fxe5 18. bxc5 exd4 19. cxd4 Be4 $132) 17... Rxf6 18. a5 (18. Rc1 e5 19. fxe5 (19. Nf3 exf4 20. Bd4 Rf7 21. c4 Nf5 $13) 19... Qxe5 $132) 18... Raf8 19. Nf3 (19. c4 e5 $1 20. fxe5 Qxe5 $132) 19... Nf5 20. Bd4 Nxd4 21. cxd4 Ne4 22. Ne5 (22. g3 g5 $1 23. fxg5 hxg5 24. Qc1 Qg7 $132) 22... Rxf4 23. Rxf4 Rxf4 24. Qc1 $1 Qxc1+ 25. Rxc1 g5 $1 {Precision until the end. Black's king requires some more space.} 26. g3 (26. Rc7 Rf2 27. Rc8+ Kg7 $11) 26... Rf2 27. Bg4 Bf5 $11) 9... c4 10. Nbd2 Ne7 {The most strategically complex position in this line. White now has quite a few different approaches:} 11. Ne1 {Preparing f2-f4 and g2-g4 and a knight transfer to c2.} (11. b3 {Now Black is just in time to create enough counterplay:} cxb3 12. Qxb3 Nc6 13. c4 (13. Ba3 Bxa3 14. Qxa3 Qa5 15. Qb2 Qb6 $11) 13... Na5 14. Qa4 dxc4 15. Nxc4 Nxc4 16. Bxc4 Rc8 {Very sharp and precise play by Fedoseev.} ({Yet it was also possible to quietly finish development and just ignore White's threats in view of the following tactics:} 16... Be7 $5 17. d5 O-O $1 18. d6 Nb6 19. dxc7 Nxa4 20. Nd4 Be4 $132) 17. Be2 (17. Bb3 Bd3 $1 18. Rd1 b5 (18... Be2 $5) 19. Qa6 Nb8 20. Qxc8+ Qxc8 21. Rxd3 {1/2-1/2 Chigaev,M (2565)-Rozum,I (2581) RUS-chT2 Sochi 2018 (9.2)} Na6 $1 22. Bb2 (22. d5 Nb4 $17) 22... Qb7 $15) 17... a6 18. d5 $1 Bc5 $1 19. d6 {0-1 Rublevsky,S (2689)-Fedoseev,V (2673) EU-Cup 32nd Novi Sad 2016 (7.6)} Qc6 20. Qxc6 Rxc6 21. Bb2 Rb6 $132) (11. a4 {Trying obtain an improved version of the b3 idea.} Nc6 12. b3 (12. Ne1 Na5 $5 13. Nc2 Be7 14. Ne3 Bh7 15. f4 O-O-O $132) 12... cxb3 {Now that the c3-pawn is not attacked by the queen, White can take back with the knight. Anyway, Black has no particular problems.} 13. Nxb3 Be7 14. Ne1 O-O 15. Bd3 Bxd3 16. Nxd3 f6 $5 17. exf6 Nxf6 $132) (11. Nh4 Bh7 12. f4 g5 $1 13. fxg5 hxg5 14. Nhf3 Nf5 {Black has played energetically and strong. To hold the balance, White needs to play very precisely now:} 15. Nxg5 $1 (15. Nb1 $2 {1-0 Oparin,G (2604)-Faizrakhmanov,R (2439) RUS-chT 24th Sochi 2017 (7.5)} f6 16. exf6 O-O-O 17. Bxg5 Bd6 18. f7 Rdf8 19. Nbd2 Bg6 $19) 15... Ne3 16. Qe1 (16. Bh5 Nxd1 17. Nxe6 Qc6 18. Bxf7+ Ke7 19. Nxc4 $1 Rg8 $5 20. Nd6 Rg6 $17) 16... Nxf1 17. Nxf1 Bg6 18. h4 $1 Be7 19. h5 Bxh5 $5 20. Qh4 O-O-O 21. Bxh5 Rdg8 22. Nxe6 $1 Bxh4 23. Nxc7 Rxh5 24. Nxd5 Nb6 25. Nxb6+ axb6 $132 {Not a necessary line, of course, but it illustrates the spirit of the position.}) 11... b5 12. Nc2 {Protecting against an immediate b5-b4. Later, the knight can be transferred to e3.} (12. f4 b4 $1 {With energetic play, Black obtains a good position.} ({Also possible but unnecessary is} 12... a5 13. Rf2 $5) 13. g4 Bh7 14. Ng2 bxc3 15. bxc3 Qa5 16. Qe1 (16. Rf3 h5 $1 17. gxh5 Nf5 $132) 16... Nc6 17. Nf3 (17. Rf3 Qb6 $5 18. Kh1 Nxd4 $1 19. cxd4 Qxd4 20. Ba3 Bxa3 21. Rxa3 O-O $44) 17... Be4 $1 18. f5 (18. Ne3 O-O-O $132) 18... Be7 19. fxe6 fxe6 20. Nf4 O-O $1 {Thanks to the activity of his pieces and White's vulnerable king, Black can afford this pawn sacrifice.} 21. Nxe6 (21. g5 hxg5 22. Nxe6 g4 $1 23. Nxf8 gxf3 $132) 21... Rf7 22. g5 Nf8 $1 $132) 12... a5 13. Ne3 (13. f4 a4 14. Ne3 Bg6 {cf7}) 13... Bg6 14. f4 (14. Bg4 {is less challenging.} h5 $5 ({A simple and sound solution is} 14... Nb6 $5 15. f4 Qd7 $1 {, with a good position for Black.}) 15. Bh3 Bd3 16. Re1 a4 $5 (16... Nc6 $5 17. g3 h4 $132) 17. Nf3 Nc6 $5 {Provoking a big mess.} (17... g6 $6 18. g3 b4 19. cxb4 Qb6 20. a3 $16 {1-0 Esipenko,A (2682)-Keymer,V (2686) Biel blitz 55th 2022 (7)}) 18. Nxd5 $1 (18. Ng5 Nb6 $15) 18... exd5 19. e6 fxe6 20. Ng5 (20. Rxe6+ $6 Be7 21. Bg5 b4 $1 22. cxb4 Nf6 $17) 20... e5 21. Qf3 $1 Nf6 22. Bf4 $1 Be4 $1 23. Nxe4 dxe4 24. Rxe4 Nxe4 25. Qxe4 Bd6 26. Bg5 $1 Be7 27. Qg6+ Kf8 28. Qf5+ Ke8 $11 {And a draw by perpetual.}) 14... a4 $1 {It was a huge discovery for me that Black's play should be not only be based on the b5-b4 advance but also on a5-a4, potentially securing the queenside for his king. In this case, White's play on the kingside can suddenly become very double-edged, as it exposes his own king.} (14... b4 15. g4 Bh7 16. f5 $36) (14... h5 15. Nf3 Nf5 16. Nxf5 Bxf5 17. Nh4 g6 18. Nxf5 exf5 $14 {This is solid for Black, but only White can try to break through.}) 15. Rf2 (15. g4 f6 $1 16. Qe1 (16. f5 $6 Bf7 $36) 16... fxe5 17. fxe5 Qb6 18. Qg3 O-O-O $132) 15... h5 $1 16. Nf3 Qb6 $5 17. g3 (17. a3 Nf5 18. Nxf5 Bxf5 19. Nh4 Be4 20. f5 exf5 21. Nxf5 Nxe5 $1 22. dxe5 Bxf5 23. Qxd5 Rc8 24. Qf3 g6 25. Be3 Bc5 $132 {Due to the weakness of the e5-pawn, only Black can be better.}) 17... Nf5 18. Nxf5 Bxf5 19. Nh4 Be4 20. Bf3 Bxf3 21. Nxf3 g6 $132 {Black is very solid. After finishing development with Be7 and 0-0, he can consider counterplay on the kingside with f7-f6.} *

